<div id="comment_64174837" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64174837" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64174837" name="comment_link_64174837" href="//hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23199107&amp;cid=64174837" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64174837)" >Why the northern states.</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64174837" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64174837); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>3</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Jarik+C-Bol">Jarik C-Bol</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Jarik+C-Bol">( 894741 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64174837">		
		on Saturday January 20, 2024 @08:22AM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23199107&amp;cid=64174837">#64174837</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64174837">Selecting the northern states makes little sense to me. It is mid winter here, and I can say from direct experience, we get less than 6 hours of usable sunlight this time of year, and lots of snow. We use solar panels on a few remote water wells, and they are fine in the summer, but in winter  it requires snowplows to go out to them and remove snow, regularly. And that is if the sun is out. Otherwise, a gas generator has to be used. If it was not so cost prohibitive to have these wells on the grid, we absolutely would. (Remote locations, far from existing power lines)
Installing large scale solar farms in this environment, where half the year there us little sunlight, and even higher maintenance requirements to use what little sunlight we get, seems hilariously wasteful of solar panels.</div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64174837">
